hare some of their stories, their excitement in publishing their work, and their creative process. I'm really proud of the work they've put in so far and in what's to come. I hope they're happy with the results.<br />&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp; That said, here's what else we're working on in class next week...<br /><br />&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp; <font color="#8d2424"><strong>Sixth Grade</strong></font>: Early next week (Monday or Tuesday) we'll finish the Inca and then quickly discuss the Aztecs and Mayans. It'll likely be the Aztecs next week and Mayans early the following week, with our Great Debate occurring either Wednesday or Thursday, May 25/26. In addition to notes and assignments, the classes are conducting more thorough research into their civilization and putting it all together into a PowerPoint/presentation of some kind that they'll use in the debate.<br />&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp; <font color="#8d2424"><strong>Seventh Grade</strong></font>: In discussing economics, the class spent the past few days relating it to Major League Baseball and focused on the question -- Does a high team salary equate to wins/championships (and in turn, more fans, more exposure and higher revenue) or is overspending not economical? We're moving on into Russia next week, where we'll end the year discussing the geography, history and economics of the country.<br />&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp; <font color="#8d2424"><strong>Eighth Grade</strong></font>: Both classes have their literature final Monday. They received a copy of the final Thursday/Friday and can use the back of the sheet to build an argument/jot down any notes needed to answer the question. It's an essay question, 2-3 pages in length, where they'll need to build and support an argument using textual evidence. The rest of the week is dedicated to the book, which will hopefully be submitted to Smashwords by the end of next week or early the following week.<br /><br />&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp; I hope everyone has a great weekend and best of luck to the 