 associate superintendents, principals and teachers will sift through binders full of documented examples of this commitment. As well, they'll speak with a few students, teachers and others about the school. Parents, too, I'm sure, just in case someone stops you in the hallway to talk.<br />&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;Additionally on Tuesday, safety patrol will attend the Tigers game against the Pittsburgh Pirates, with lunch at Hockeytown beforehand. We also have Upland Hills Farm coming in Wednesday. Should be a fun and interesting time for all.<br />&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp; Here's what to expect in class next week...<br />&#8203;<br />&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp; <strong><font color="#8d2424">Sixth Grade</font></strong>: The classes just finished making board games representing Latin America and its physical geography. We'll get into physical features' effects on the climate and vegetation of the region and will have a quiz on Wednesday or Thursday, before moving into the history of the region. Namely, the Inca, Maya and Aztec civilizations.&nbsp; <br />&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp; <font color="#8d2424"><strong>Seventh Grade</strong></font>: We started our unit on Europe this week, which encompasses a mini-market economy. Everyone chose a European country to research -- geography, history, culture, language, economy, etc. -- and a product associated with that country (Greek Mythology trading cards for Greece or crepes for France). With their research, they'll write a 4-6 page paper about their country. They'll also develop their product and conduct a cost-analysis of it for a market economy day at the end of the month.<br />&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp; <font color="#8d2424"><strong>Eighth Grade</strong></font>: We read the most important chapters in <em>The Giver</em>&nbsp;this week and will move along rather quickly in the next week. Things are about to pick up steam in the novel, and I'd like to sustain that momentum all the way through, so there'll be quite a bit of reading done for homework next week, as well as in class with discussions and varying activities. We'll also begin focusing on the end-of-novel paper comparing and contrasting <em>The Giver</em> with another dystopian novel of students' choosing. <br /><br />&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp; I hope everyone has a great weekend!<br />&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp; Mr. Hakim&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;. &nbsp;&nbsp;</div>]]></content:encoded></item><item><title><![CDATA[Friday 3-18: looking ahead]]></title><link><![CDATA[http://mrhakimsclass.weebly.com/friday-updates/friday-3-18-looking-ahead]]></link><comments><![CDATA[http://mrhakimsclass.weebly.com/friday-updates/friday-3-18-looking-ahead#comments]]></comments><pubDate>Fri, 18 Mar 2016 20:30:51 GMT</pubDate><category><![CDATA[Uncategorized]]></category><guid isPermaLink="false">http://mrhakimsclass.weebly.com/friday-updates/friday-3-18-looking-ahead</guid><description><![CDATA[Parents,&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp; This week is a quick update. Just a few reminders, the first is regarding the St. Leo's Book Drive -- if you haven't already, please donate any new or gently used books. It's truly a great sight with all the books filling up the table in the main hallway. Also, Monday is a $1 jeans day, sports team colors day. Wear your favorite team's colors that day, so I'm looking forward to seeing a sea of scarlet and gray walking the halls.&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;Here's what else to  [...] ]]></description><content:encoded><![CDATA[<div class="paragraph" style="text-align:left;">Parents,<br /><br />&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp; This week is a quick update. Just a few reminders, the first is regarding the St. Leo's Book Drive -- if you haven't already, please donate any new or gently used books. It's truly a great sight with all the books filling up the table in the main hallway. Also, Monday is a $1 jeans day, sports team colors day. Wear your favorite team's colors that day, so I'm looking forward to seeing a sea of scarlet and gray walking the halls.<br />&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;Here's what else t